04312nam a22007095i 9780748636136DE-B159720220306030904.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220306t20222012stk    fo  d z      eng d  a2013487492  a97807486361367 a10.1515/97807486361362doi  a(DE-B1597)616063  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT00aPN1993.5.I88bH33 2014 4aPN1993.5.I88bH33 2014 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.430945223  aAP 449392rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7516:6981 aHaaland, Torunn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aItalian Neorealist Cinema /cTorunn Haaland. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTraditions in World Cinema : TWC00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tTraditions in World Cinema -- t1. A moment and a country -- t2. Realism and neorealism -- t3. Literary neorealism: narration and testimony -- t4. Rossellini’s cities of war and resistance -- t5. Wandering among De Sica’s urbanites: shoeshiners, bicycle thieves, miraculous outcasts and a man with a dog -- t6. Visconti’s worlds of aestheticism and ideology: between tradition and invention, from country to city -- t7. Faces and spaces of neorealism: from dystopian cities to utopian countries -- t8. The journey beyond neorealism: streetwalkers, political rebels, antimafi a resisters, stolen children and unwanted citizens -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow has Italian neorealist cinema changed the boundaries of cinematic narration and representation? In this new study, Torunn Haaland argues that neorealism was a cultural moment based on individual optiques. She accounts for the tradition’s coherence in terms of its moral commitment to creating critical viewing experiences around underrepresented realities and marginalised people. By examining both acclaimed masterpieces and lesser known works, parallels are drawn to realist theories and to past and present cinematic traditions. The ways in which successive generations of directors have readopted, negotiated and broken with the themes and aesthetics of neorealist film are discussed and evaluated, along with neorealist tendencies in other arts, such as literature.An engaging and informative read for students and scholars in Italian Studies, Italian Neorealist Cinema presents a new approach to a key cinematic tradition, and so is essential reading for everyone working in the field of Film Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictureszItaly. 0aRealism in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074863613640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748636136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748636136/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK